<div id="review_3031139350" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3031139350" />
    <a title="Evgeny" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9340136-evgeny"><img alt="Evgeny" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1544797852p2/9340136.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3031139350?book_show_action=true">Dec 20, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Evgeny" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Evgeny" href="/user/show/9340136-evgeny">Evgeny</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9340136-evgeny?shelf=hercule-poirot">hercule-poirot</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9340136-evgeny?shelf=crime-and-mystery">crime-and-mystery</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3031139350" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1150155821154539640">Elinor Carlisle received a vile anonymous letter implying that her old rich aunt whose death Elinor and her cousin Roderick patiently awaited as they never bothered doing that pesky thingy called work as thus were penniless, was under the influence of a local young girl and was about to leave all the money to her. <br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1576893721i/28644174._SX540_.jpg' alt='Letter' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/>We cannot have it, can we? No wonder Elinor and Roderick dropped everything and finally came to visit their aunt. <br/><br/>Here I need to say I felt Mary Gerrard who visited the old lady in que</span>
  <span id="freeText1150155821154539640" style="display:none">Elinor Carlisle received a vile anonymous letter implying that her old rich aunt whose death Elinor and her cousin Roderick patiently awaited as they never bothered doing that pesky thingy called work as thus were penniless, was under the influence of a local young girl and was about to leave all the money to her. <br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1576893721i/28644174._SX540_.jpg" alt="Letter" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>We cannot have it, can we? No wonder Elinor and Roderick dropped everything and finally came to visit their aunt. <br><br>Here I need to say I felt Mary Gerrard who visited the old lady in question daily deserved all her money as opposed to her so-called relatives who rarely bothered to. Even if her interest was pure monetary - and there was no indication this was the case. <br><br>In any way, two dead bodies later Elinor became a prime suspect in at least one murder. Every single clue was against her. A local doctor who believed in her innocence came to Hercule Poirot and convinced him to do his own investigation. <br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1576894237i/28644217._SX540_.jpg" alt="Doctor" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>The more Poirot investigated the more clues he uncovered pointing to Elinor as a culprit. <br><br>On the positive side this is the first time in Poirot investigation where even Poirot efforts resulted in finding even more damning evidence against the person he was trying to help. On the negative side it was possible to figure out the real culprit very early. On the negative side again it was not Poirot who explained everything at the end. Agatha Christie decided to play Perry Mason and left the explanations to a layer in a court session. <br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1576893808i/28644175._SX540_.jpg" alt="Perry Mason" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>I personally like Poirot more than that Perry Mason wannabe. <br><br>The characters were interesting as usual, but I could not care less about Elinor. She was a typical parasite living off her aunt and made famous Snow Queen look like the most emotional lady in fiction ever. <br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1576893913i/28644199._SX540_.jpg" alt="Snow Queen" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>In other words, I could not care less if she was found guilty - and this usually takes some effort from the author. <br><br>This is still a Poirot book which means my rating would be <b>3.5 stars</b> rounded up, but this is one of the weaker Poirot (I continue pretending The Big Four never happened). Still worth reading in any case.</span>
