    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1190697661" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1190697661" />
    <a title="Kavita" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5858699-kavita"><img alt="Kavita" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1315387023p2/5858699.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1190697661?book_show_action=true">Feb 04, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kavita" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kavita" href="/user/show/5858699-kavita">Kavita</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=uk">uk</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=movie-was-better">movie-was-better</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=golden-age-mystery">golden-age-mystery</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1190697661" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13161305761632203363">Eleanor Carlisle is accused of poisoning Mary Gerrard. She had the motive, the means, and the opportunity down pat. And as all of us budding amateur detectives know, these are the three golden rules of detection. However, Dr Peter Lord is convinced that she is innocent and ropes in good ole Poirot to work out how. However, twist the facts as you might, money, love, revenge, or mercy, the pointer points towards Eleanor. <br/><br/>I thought the plot was brilliant and the murderer was conjured up out of the </span>
  <span id="freeText13161305761632203363" style="display:none">Eleanor Carlisle is accused of poisoning Mary Gerrard. She had the motive, the means, and the opportunity down pat. And as all of us budding amateur detectives know, these are the three golden rules of detection. However, Dr Peter Lord is convinced that she is innocent and ropes in good ole Poirot to work out how. However, twist the facts as you might, money, love, revenge, or mercy, the pointer points towards Eleanor. <br /><br />I thought the plot was brilliant and the murderer was conjured up out of the hat - but totally believable. I just wish the execution had been better. A lot of the climax takes place through dry court proceedings and there simply isn't enough interactions between characters in the last portion of the book. This could have been exceedingly creepy but just ended up as a great plot moderately well executed. I think this was the one book that the show did so much better. <br /><br />Poirot does not appear till much later in the book, but that is not necessarily a problem. In fact, this gave time for establishing the characters and the setting quite well. I enjoyed the interplay between the nurses and the quiet village life, suddenly marred by murder. No one does atmosphere quite as well as Christie!<br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13161305761632203363" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

